keywords = {Energy cloud, Smart Energy, Internet of Energy, Transactive Energy, Energy hub},
abstract = {The evolution of energy systems has placed end users in a central role in dynamic, flexible and decentralised cloud-based energy management models. Different terms have been used to represent these new energy systems, with different conceptualisations and systemic scopes. Hence, this article aims to identify the terms used to refer to new models of cloud-based energy systems, temporally and geographically map their use, bringing the definitions that underlie these terms and their similarities and differences. We conducted a systematic literature review to identify relevant terms and concepts to achieve this goal. Subsequently, a meta-analysis was performed to map these terms, allowing us to analyse their interrelationships and identify trends in their usage across scientific literature. The article's results demonstrate the existence of five groups of terminologies: Energy Cloud, Smart Energy, Internet of Energy, Transactive Energy, and Energy Hub, with the other terms appearing as derivations of these. In this sequence is the amplitude of the conceptual scope, from the one that addresses all the physical and virtual infrastructures of the electric power systems to the one that contemplates physical infrastructures with connections to the Internet in local electric systems. These results can help to consolidate these terminologies, facilitating the understanding of the concepts and their applications, in addition to demonstrating that there is a need for actions to develop policies and legal support that support this greater autonomy and freedom given to users of these energy systems.}
}
